                <note rend="inline" type="source">863.01/3–3045: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Alexander C. Kirk</persName>,
                        Political Adviser, Allied Force Headquarters</hi>,<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d1069fn47">Mr. Kirk was also Ambassador to Italy.</note>
                    <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Caserta</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-03-30T16:00:00+01:00"
                            >March 30, 1945—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 30—10:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1242. OSS<note n="48" xml:id="d1069fn48">Office of Strategic Services.</note>
                    reports that General Velebit<note n="49" xml:id="d1069fn49">Maj. Gen. Vladimir
                        L. Velebit, chief of the military mission in London of the National
                        Liberation army and the Partisan detachments of Yugoslavia.</note> stated on
                    March 28 during informal discussion of plans for occupation of Austria and in
                    reply to a question whether Yugoslavs would occupy Villach and <pb facs="1326"
                        n="1314" xml:id="pg_1314"/> Klagenfurt after Nazi collapse, that Yugoslavs
                    would occupy both these places as “they belong to Yugoslavia.” In addition,
                    Yugoslavia intended to occupy certain “enemy territory”.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
